solution:
\begin{solution}
This is a separable differential equation that we
solve in the usual way.
\begin{align*}
\diff{y}{x} &= -xy^3\\
- \frac{\dee{y}}{y^3} &=  x\ \dee{x}\\
\int -\frac{\dee{y}}{y^3} &= \int x\ \dee{x}\\
- \frac{y^{-2}}{-2} &= \frac{x^2}{2}+C\\
 y^{-2}&=x^2+2C. \tag{$*$}
\intertext{To have $y=-\frac{1}{4}$ when $x=0$, we must choose $C$ to obey}{\Big(-\frac{1}{4} \Big)}^{-2}& =0 +2C\\
16&= 2C
