We integrate by parts, with $u=\sin(2x)$ or $\cos(2x)$ and $\dee{v}=e^{-x}\,\dee{x}$.
That is, $v=-e^{-x}$.
\begin{alignat*}{3}
I_1&=\int_0^\infty e^{-x} \sin(2x)\,\dee{x}
&&=\lim_{R\rightarrow\infty}\int_0^R e^{-x} \sin(2x)\,\dee{x} \\
&&&=
