\noindent (b) We can cancel out the square root if we use a trig substitution.
Substitute $x=\sqrt{2}\tan y$, $\dee{x}=\sqrt{2}\sec^2 y\,\dee{y}$.
\begin{align*}
\int_0^{\sqrt{2}}\frac{1}{(2+x^2)^{3/2}}\,\dee{x}
