\end{question}

solution:
\begin{solution}
If we try naively then we get $0/0$, so we simplify first:
\begin{align*}
  \frac{x-2}{x^2-4} &= \frac{x-2}{(x-2)(x+2)} = \frac{1}{x+2}
\end{align*}
Hence the limit is $\displaystyle \lim_{x\rightarrow2} \frac{1}{x+2} = 1/4$.\end{solution}

question:
